This is why we love Paris. A couple of streets away from busy tourist sites you find yourself in a beautiful oasis of calm, grab a pastry or a hunk of baguette and chill out in a park.

Quiet place, you can breathe an air of times gone by, with children playing, people sitting leisurely on the benches to relax in a simple way. On a bench, immersed in a small capsule of space and time that isolates you from the surrounding world and daily worries. The sumptuous looking neo-Gothic church of S Genevieve decorates the background of the area.

Super well maintained by Armand, the gardener who has unparalleled know-how (and who also takes care of all the vegetation around the Saint Clotilde Basilica). Close to the Las Cases School, therefore very busy from 4:30 p.m. on weekdays. Much quieter on weekends. Play area for children. Beautiful lawn. Numerous benches in the shade or in the sun depending on your preferences. 2 beautiful statues. A nice rest area for everyone!‚ù§

That's everything I love about Paris. At the bend of a street, you come face to face with a gate of a garden, a square, a park. You go in and wander around for a few minutes. Sit on a bench and watch the people walking there, the children playing, the birds chirping... You start to dream... This is Paris and you can't find this anywhere else in the world.
Nice for lunch, lots of benches in the shade. But very busy especially with all the construction sites nearby

I was there by Hazard and surprised when I saw the beautiful church, I stayed a good while, and said to myself that at that time men knew how to work, the details, the stones, the thickness of the walls, (Gothic churches are really beautiful)
Small square of tranquility facing the very beautiful Sainte-Clotilde church. This small square is well maintained and well frequented. Public toilets on the side.
Great place to relax, several people, but all respectful of the quiet

Small square facing the Saint Clotilde church. Perfect moment of relaxation and rest after visiting this beautiful Parisian district. Close to charming mansions, the National Assembly and the unmissable Rodin Museum.

Very nicely organized, this little square blossoms pleasantly in the shade of the charming Saint Clothilde basilica! And, precisely, Le square honors the French composer, organist and musicographer Samuel Rousseau (1853-1904) who was chapel master at the Sainte-Clotilde basilica....! We shouldn't say it but... it's the calmest and most peaceful place on the left bank. Few people and the benevolent shadow of Saint Clotilde.
Very beautiful park located in the city center. It is very pleasant to spend a little time there.
It is a good park with a small park for the little ones and a lawn for those who prefer to play ball or tag etc.
